model.effective_equation: Nonrelativistic s-wave Schrödinger equation for relative motion with an effective potential V(r)=μ φ(r)=-μ c^2 u(r).
model.ansatz: λπ-constrained three-range (barrier+tail split; channel-split (k,q)): same geometry as step 7.13.8 but allow separate (k_t,q_t) for triplet and (k_s,q_s) for singlet, selected jointly by envelope/tolerance criteria before fitting per dataset. Singlet restricts V2_s>=0.

singlet: a_s (np low-energy; fits V1_s,V2_s>=0; barrier+tail split fixed by λπ)
r_s (np low-energy; fits V1_s,V2_s>=0; barrier+tail split fixed by λπ)

positioning: Phenomenological constraint (effective model), not a first-principles derivation of nuclear forces.
The ansatz class is intentionally low-parameter to avoid 'arbitrary function fit'.

To limit arbitrariness, constrain geometry by λπ and split the tail into barrier+tail, but allow channel-dependent (k_t,q_t)/(k_s,q_s); select them jointly by envelope/tolerance criteria before fitting per dataset.

sources.dataset: NIST Cuu CODATA constants (mp,mn,md) for deuteron binding baseline

tail_constraint.barrier_tail_rule: Vb = barrier_height_factor*V3_mean, Vt = tail_depth_factor*V3_mean (no mean-preserving constraint)

fit_triplet.note: Triplet: λπ-constrained geometry + barrier+tail split beyond R2 (free tail depth); channel-split (k_t,q_t)/(k_s,q_s) scan with envelope/tolerance criteria, then fit per dataset.

fit_singlet.fit_mode: Shared geometry (R1,R2,R3=R2+λπ) + barrier+tail split; singlet uses its own (k_s,q_s) while triplet uses (k_t,q_t); fit (V1_s,V2_s>=0) to match (a_s,r_s).
fit_singlet.note_fit: bisection did not converge; using best endpoint (barrier+tail)
fit_singlet.note: Singlet: uses shared (R1,R2) but allows channel-dependent barrier/tail scaling; fits (V1_s,V2_s) by (a_s,r_s). v2s is a prediction.

tail_constraint.barrier_tail_rule: Vb = barrier_height_factor*V3_mean, Vt = tail_depth_factor*V3_mean (no mean-preserving constraint)

notes: Eq.(18) and Eq.(19) are two phase-shift analyses in the same primary source; their difference is treated as an analysis-dependent systematics proxy.
Triplet fit is performed per dataset to expose sensitivity of the inferred u-profile to that proxy.
In step 7.9.7/7.9.8/7.13.3/7.13.4/7.13.5/7.13.6/7.13.7/7.13.8/7.13.8.1/7.13.8.2, singlet r_s is fitted per dataset; v2s is the remaining differential prediction.

acceptance_criteria: Under the λπ-constrained three-range (barrier+tail split; free tail depth) ansatz class with channel-split (k_t,q_t)/(k_s,q_s) selected by cross-systematics, after fitting triplet targets and fitting singlet (a_s,r_s) with V2_s>=0, both triplet v2t and singlet (r_s,v2s) should be compatible with the observed envelopes (eq18–eq19).
If any of (triplet v2t, singlet r_s, singlet v2s) falls outside the analysis-dependent envelope, the ansatz class is rejected as a representation of the nuclear-scale u-profile.

policy.selection_rule: Prefer any (k_t,q_t,k_s,q_s) that makes triplet (a_t,r_t) stable and v2t within envelope, and singlet (r_s,v2s) within envelope; tie-break by minimal max_dist(v2), then |Δr_s|, then triplet AR penalty, then minimal channel split |k_t-k_s|+|q_t-q_s|.
